Visual Check

plot(ns)

hist(ns, breaks = 20)

plot(density(ns, bw = 5))

hist(ns, breaks = 20, freq = F)
lines(density(ns, bw = 5), col = "blue")

mean(ns)
## [1] 176.6333
sd(ns)
## [1] 13.47299
n <- length(ns)
sd(ns) * sqrt(n-1) / sqrt(n)
## [1] 13.40546
library(MASS)
fitdistr(ns, "normal")
##       mean           sd     
##   176.6333105    13.4054562 
##  (  1.3405456) (  0.9479089)
hist(ns, breaks = 20, freq = F)
lines(density(ns, bw = 5), col = "blue")
lines(sort(ns), dnorm(sort(ns), mean = 176.6, sd = 13.4), col = "red")

TASK #2.1 Sigma Rules

  • Check 1-2-3 sigma rules for normal distribution

Central Limit Theorem

set.seed(8)
population <- rnorm(1000000, 0, 1)
sample_10 <- sample(population, 10)
sample_50 <- sample(population, 50)
sample_100 <- sample(population, 100)

mean(sample_10)
## [1] -0.05881956
mean(sample_50)
## [1] 0.2179049
mean(sample_100)
## [1] 0.05841155
sample_means <- numeric(30)
set.seed(4)
for (i in 1:30) {
    sample_means[i] <- mean(sample(population, 10))
}
hist(sample_means)

sample_means <- numeric(30)
set.seed(4)
for (i in 1:30) {
    sample_means[i] <- mean(sample(population, 100))
}
hist(sample_means)

Confidence Intervals

SE <- function(x) {sd(x) / sqrt(length(x))}

SE(sample_10)
## [1] 0.3693324
SE(sample_50)
## [1] 0.1283063
SE(sample_100)
## [1] 0.09563558
qt( (1-0.95)/2, df = 9)
## [1] -2.262157
mean(sample_10) - 2.262157*SE(sample_10)
## [1] -0.8943075
t.test(sample_10)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  sample_10
## t = -0.15926, df = 9, p-value = 0.877
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.8943075  0.7766684
## sample estimates:
##   mean of x 
## -0.05881956
t.test(sample_100)$conf.int
## [1] -0.1313502  0.2481733
## attr(,"conf.level")
## [1] 0.95
t.test(sample_100, conf.level = 0.99)$conf.int
## [1] -0.1927663  0.3095894
## attr(,"conf.level")
## [1] 0.99
